# Testing Orchesty Components

Tests use Jest with `ts-jest`. Config is in `jest.config.js`.
Test files must match `**/__tests__/*.ts` and live under `src/`.

## Test File Structure

```
src/
  MyService/
    Connector/
      MyServiceGetResource.ts
    __tests__/
      MyServiceGetResource.ts       # test file (no .test suffix needed)
      Data/
        MyServiceGetResource/
          input.json                # input ProcessDto body
          output.json               # expected output body
          mock.json                 # first HTTP mock
          mock1.json                # second HTTP mock (if needed)
```

### Prefixed Variants

For multiple test cases use a prefix (e.g. `error-`):

```
Data/MyServiceGetResource/
  error-input.json
  error-output.json
  error-mock.json
```

## Using NodeTester

`NodeTester` auto-loads input/output/mock files and runs assertions:

```typescript
import NodeTester from '@orchesty/nodejs-sdk/dist/test/Testers/NodeTester';
import { container } from '@orchesty/nodejs-sdk';
import { createLoggerMockedServer, createMetricsMockedServer } from '@orchesty/nodejs-sdk/dist/test/MockServer';

// Register your nodes before tests (same as index.ts)
import '../../index';

let tester: NodeTester;

beforeAll(() => {
    createMetricsMockedServer();
    createLoggerMockedServer();
    tester = new NodeTester(container, __filename);
});

describe('MyServiceGetResource', () => {
    it('processes action', async () => {
        await tester.testConnector('my-service-get-resource');
    });

    it('handles error case', async () => {
        await tester.testConnector('my-service-get-resource', 'error-');
    });
});
```

### Testing Different Node Types

```typescript
await tester.testConnector('connector-name');       // AConnector
await tester.testBatch('batch-name');               // ABatchNode
await tester.testCustomNode('custom-node-name');    // ACommonNode
```

## Mock File Format

Each `mock.json` defines an HTTP call to intercept:

```json
{
    "http": "GET https://api.example.com/v1/resources/123",
    "code": 200,
    "body": { "id": "123", "name": "Test Resource" },
    "headers": { "Content-Type": "application/json" }
}
```

## Key Rules

- Always create `Data/` fixtures — never hardcode request/response bodies in test files.
- Mock file index matches call order: `mock.json` (1st call), `mock1.json` (2nd call).
- The test lifecycle in `.jest/testLifecycle.ts` already sets up logger and metrics mocks.
- Use prefixes to cover happy-path and error scenarios separately.
